 :tx/rationale "DOG-FOODING FRICTION POINTS — the 5 things that slow me down most:\n\n1. F(S) IS INERT. It has been 0.67 the entire session despite closing 44 tasks, adding 68 tests, creating 4 EPICs, and implementing 3 major subsystems (TSV, spec_graph_neighbors, compile-to-prompt). The metric does not reflect the work. Root cause: the V (validation) component requires formal FBW witnesses, not just tests existing. And the C (coverage) component checks spec-impl link density, which doesn't change much when I'm implementing kernel functions (they don't have :impl/implements links by default). F(S) measures FORMAL VERIFICATION STATUS, not IMPLEMENTATION PROGRESS. These are different things and the system conflates them. PROPOSED FIX: add a separate progress metric P(t) = closed_tasks / total_tasks that responds to actual work, alongside F(S) for formal verification.\n\n2. HARVEST URGENCY ALERT FATIGUE. The NEG-HARVEST-001 warning fires after ~10 transactions. During active coding, I hit 10 tx in 3-4 minutes. The warning becomes noise I reflexively ignore. The urgency formula treats all tx equally, but a batch of task closes (10 tx in 30 seconds) is NOT the same as 10 knowledge-producing observations over an hour. PROPOSED FIX: weight urgency by knowledge production rate, not raw tx count. Task closes and status checks should barely register; novel observations should register heavily.\n\n3. THE TASK TITLE PROBLEM IS ONLY HALF SOLVED. short_title strips BACKGROUND sections from list display, but the FULL title is still stored as one massive string in :task/title. This bloats the store, slows queries, and makes the JSON output huge. Task-as-ACP (structured task entities with :task/background, :task/acceptance, :task/approach as separate attributes) is the real fix but isn't implemented. Every task I created this session crammed 500+ chars into the title field.\n\n4. PARALLEL AGENT FILE CONFLICTS. I launched 3 agents in parallel (TSV-TEST, CTP-1, AR-2) on disjoint file sets, but the AR-4 agent later modified MethodologyGaps in guidance.rs which broke my CTP-2 changes in seed.rs. The dependency was STRUCTURAL (shared type), not FILE-based. Braid's topology system tracks file-level coupling but not type-level coupling. When Agent A adds a field to a struct that Agent B uses, the conflict is invisible until cargo check fails.\n\n5. CEREMONY COST OF BRAID OBSERVE. Each braid observe call costs ~3 seconds (store load + reconciliation scan + datom write). Over 44 tasks, I ran observe ~15 times = 45 seconds of pure ceremony. This doesn't include the TOKEN cost of formulating the observation text. The Zero-Cost Methodology (auto-observation from command outputs) would eliminate this, but it's not implemented. The irony: the observe command is the MOST important for knowledge capture, but its ceremony cost makes agents skip it."
